In this section, we focus on the concept of summarization. We showed previously how visualizing, sorting and filtering data can help you quickly get a sense for what is going on in your data. This preliminary work is important because it enables you to be more efficient in designing your analysis. But we have yet to see Microsoft Excel's best tool for summarizing data: the Pivot Table. Being able to create meaningful Pivot Tables is one of those skills that separates the truly sophisticated end users from the rest. When the data you have to analyze grows beyond a few hundred rows and ten columns it quickly becomes unfeasible to get a feel for it without summarizing your data efficiently. The Pivot Table is the instrument of choice for this task.

## Skills

  -	Importing data from a text file
  - Creating Pivot Tables
  - Refreshing data in a Pivot Tables
  - Finding data with MATCH and INDEX

## Exercise Overview

**Objective** Practice importing data from text files and work with larger datasets - over 3,000 rows. Practice data summarization techniques and intermediate and advanced computations on a mid-sized dataset.

**Scenario** Cousin Anna is finally impressed with your work, she complimented you on your market share analysis. She now suggests that you should perform some unit economics computations. This type of analysis is important to establish the financial viability of a business. You will do so by looking at individual orders generated by a real pizza restaurant. It is usually very difficult to get this type of data, because businesses are very protective of it. However, you are lucky! Your cousin Vinnie (Anna's brother) owns a local Domino's pizza franchise. He is willing to share with you his data. He is not "very good at computers" so he just sent you a .txt file directly exported from his restaurant's Point of Sale (POS) system. It is up to you to import it in Excel and extract some meaning from it. You have come a long way since you started this project. You are confident you can do it, and so is cousin Anna.

